article.headline: Duncan, Nesterovic each score 21
article.linkText: Inside track: Spurs' big men too hot for Miami
article.story:
MIAMI (AP) -- The San Antonio Spurs used their weekend in Florida to rejuvenate themselves. Tim Duncan beat the halftime buzzer with his second 3-pointer of the season, finishing with 21 points and 19 rebounds Saturday night as the Spurs rolled to an 86-70 victory over the Miami Heat. Miami's 70 points marked the fewest scored against San Antonio this season. "We've learned our defensive schemes the last couple of games, and we're enforcing it a bit," Duncan said. "We're understanding what we can do and we're helping each other a lot." Coming off an 11-point victory in Orlando on Friday night that snapped a four-game losing streak, the Spurs got a season-high 21 points and 13 rebounds from Rasho Nesterovic and 11 assists from Tony Parker. San Antonio hadn't beaten the Magic and Heat on the same trip since January, 1998. "It's a good win for us in a back-to-back situation on the road," Spurs coach Gregg Popovich said. "You always feel good about those kinds of wins. They're always special. "Those somehow mean a little more to you, and it helps you get your team together." Lamar Odom had 17 points to lead Miami, which equaled its lowest scoring output of the season. The Heat also scored 70 points at Houston on Nov. 11. "We are just like a football team that cannot score in the red zone," Odom said. "We are missing layups and free throws. When you do that, then you put a lot of pressure on your defense." San Antonio used its size advantage to build a 16-point halftime lead and stayed in control the rest of the way. The Heat trailed by as many as 20 points in the second half and never got closer than nine. All five Spurs starters scored in double figures. The Spurs hit 16 of 24 free throws; the Heat 6 of 10. Duncan had 19 points and 11 rebounds to help the Spurs build a 45-29 halftime lead. It was Miami's lowest-scoring half of the season. "When you play a team with the size of San Antonio, it gets hard for us," Miami coach Stan Van Gundy said. "And when it gets hard for us, we lose confidence. That drains our energy, and I didn't like that tonight." San Antonio's size advantage played a big part in Miami's big men shooting 4-of-21 in the first half. Brian Grant was 2-of-10 and Odom 1-of-6. The Spurs also had 13 second-chance points to the Heat's four. "We got really good (defensive) pressure," Nesterovic said. "It makes our big guys' job much easier." Duncan had 11 points and seven rebounds, and Nesterovic scored eight points as San Antonio took a 24-13 lead after one quarter. "It's coming together," Duncan said of his playing alongside Nesterovic. "It's still a young relationship. He's a skilled player. I'm learning what he can do. We're learning each other's strengths and weaknesses."

Game notes
Miami's previous low output for a half was 32 points, in the second half at San Antonio on Nov. 4. ... Heat center Loren Woods replaced Udonis Haslem in the starting lineup for the second consecutive game. ... Van Gundy said his team's development will be stressed during practice and film sessions. "We're not going to develop (players) at the expense of winning games," he said. ... The Spurs split their Florida swing last season, losing at Miami on Feb. 1 before winning at Orlando two nights later. ... Miami fell to 1-9 vs. the Western Conference. ... The Spurs have beaten the Heat five consecutive times, with Miami scoring fewer than 74 in each of the last four meetings.
